<TABLE BGCOLOR=#ccffff WIDTH=60% BORDER=0 BORDERCOLOR=#0000ff> <TR><TD><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="3" COLOR="#000000"><FONT SIZE=-1> <A NAME=POST1896>  By <B><!-Email-!><A HREF="javascript:alert('The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.')" onMouseOver="window.status = 'The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.'; return true"><!-/Email-!><!-Name-!>LadyElayna<!-/Name-!></A></B> on Thursday, March 21, 2002 - 12:22 am:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><P> <!-Text-!> The Lady Elayna sat stunned, her knitting forgotten in her lap, a smile dancing playfully on her lips, as she gazed at the crude writing upon the scroll she now held before her. <BR> <BR>&#34;What is it, Laney?&#34; asked Zareal, standing on tip-toes to peer over Elayna&#39;s shoulder. <BR> <BR>&#34;Ah...&#39;tis but a wee request fer aid, m&#39;dove.&#34; She replied, as she rolled the vellum note efficiently and tucked it in her pocket.  <BR> <BR>&#34;&#39;Tis nothin&#39; ye ha&#39;e need to fret o&#39;er.&#34; The Lady pulled a small cookie from her basket and handed it to the wee one. &#34;There be some of yer unicorn milk in the pantry, hon, the chocolate kind like ye love...go an&#39; fetch it an&#39; ha&#39;e yer cookie now.&#34; <BR> <BR>Elayna watched the tiny Mentalist dart gleefully, treat in hand, towards the kitchen in the Great Hall, and the Lady smiled. &#34;Ah, ye are a wee lass, but a power to be reckon&#39;d with, no lie!&#34; Elayna chuckled and glanced about to see if any of the others had noticed the Guard&#39;s note...and breathed a sigh of relief. <BR> <BR>Indeed, good Nebbish had kept the entertainment with his constant tossing his daggars about and catching them in his teeth, while Fleeg attempted to toss poor Nebbish about as well...Elayna shook her head and smiled. <BR> <BR>&#34;Ah, but I do love it here,&#34; she whispered, and then tucked her knitting needles into the yarn, pushed back from the great table and stood. <BR> <BR>&#34;Where ye headed, Lass?&#34; asked Gorak. <BR> <BR>Elayna winked at him and pulled forth another cookie from her pocket and waggled it in front of him. &#34;Now, methinks sommin ha&#39;e been into the sweets a bit early this eve, eh, Boss? An&#39; now I ha&#39;e to traipse all the way back to me home an&#39; do a bit more bakin&#39; would seem.&#34;  Elayna winked at the Guildmaster and offered him the cookie. <BR> <BR>&#34;Aye, Lass, &#39;twould seem so...&#34; Gorak&#39;s words were cut short by the arrival of Arroe with his latest harvest of beets and armor he&#39;d dug up out at the farm. <BR> <BR>&#34;I&#39;ll just be off then..headed home a bit...dinner&#39;s laid out in the kitchen...fer ye all...mind ye no leave a mess now!&#34; She glanced about and noticed none watching, and quickly scribbled a note, tied it with a bit of yarn and pulling her cloak about her shoulders, she left. <BR> <BR>As she closed the door behind her, she heard the familiar grunt of a badger...but it didn&#39;t bare its teeth at her approach as the ones in the wild are wont to do, and she smiled and reached out her hand to let it sniff, then giggled as its cold nose burrowed towards her pocket. &#34;Ah! Ye&#39;ll be needin&#39; some payment, then, eh, good Badger?&#34; Elayna pulled a cookie from her pocket and as the badger munched happily, she tied the small scroll about its neck. &#34;There now, off ye go, an&#39; dinna straggle! There be a lady waitin&#39; on ye, an&#39; a feast to be prepared!&#34; <BR> <BR>Elayna straightened and without hesitation breathed a word of prayer then began her chant...and as the dust whirled about her, she sped away, racing towards her home. <BR> <BR>&#34;Dwarven....my oh my will the miracles ne&#39;er cease! The Goddess &#39;erself is surely smilin&#39; upon this one, this day...and he wrote it in Elven! Bless his soul!&#34; Elayna&#39;s grin broadened as she opened the door, and dumped her cloak unceremoniously on the chair, already rolling up her sleeves to begin the her work. <BR> <BR>She had learned many arts from her mother, a great Healer in Connla, yet one skill that ne&#39;er failed was indeed her culinary gift. Elayna had spent years in the kitchen, learning that prayers and chants and hunting and defending were all worthless if yer belly be without, and now, as she stood in her own kitchen, surrounded by the feast she quickly and easily prepared, she found herself thinking of how proud her mother would be to see that even in this day, with wars rampant and death all too common, on this day, her daughter was a woman...helping another woman...whose husband acted without thought, yet whose bravery knew no bounds when it came to keeping his woman happy. <BR> <BR>The Celtic Lady  packed the last basket and stepped back, the back of her hand pushing a blonde curl away from her face, and she surveyed her work, a smile upon her face. <BR> <BR>&#34;Ah this should do..he dinne mention a number an&#39; Goddess knows I&#39;ve n&#39;er been to a Dwarven feast but surely, if this would feed my clan, then it shall do the Lady Diamond&#39;s as well!&#34; <BR> <BR>She clapped her hands together and brushed the flour from her vest, then began her encantations. <BR> <BR>This too was a gift from her mother...and this was Elayna&#39;s secret that very few knew of...for many accepted her treats and knew better than to question how her stores n&#39;er ran dry...and she closed her eyes and chanted and then pulled forth a small, plain, wooden box and opened it. <BR> <BR>As she whispered her spell, the baskets began to waver, as if moving through veils and one by one they simply slid into nonexistence, until the last one disappeared. <BR> <BR>Elayna opened her eyes and closed the lid of the box, then slipped it into her satchel. She retrieved her cloak, brushed it off and fastened it about her slender neck, and slipped quietly out into the darkness, to head for Midgard, and to cash in a favor a certain Giant owed her...so that this eve the Lady Diamond would not go without, and the good Storm would not, after all, be sleeping on the couch. <BR> <BR>And it was many hours before she arrived safely home once more, her package delivered, guarded by the Giant and surely Rokfyst himself, with Viddl and Vaijon would see to it that none disturbed the feast that lay hidden in Rokfyst&#39;s precious Log, waiting for Storm to retrieve it, as she&#39;d asked in the note she sent home with the little Badger from Midgard. <BR> <BR>And that night the Lady Warden slept at peace, and she smiled thinking of the Dwarven feast that had been prepared by a Celtic lass, and it was good. <!-/Text-!> <P> 
