<!-Post: 2021-!><!-Time: 1019681183-!>
<TABLE BGCOLOR=#ccffff WIDTH=60% BORDER=0 BORDERCOLOR=#0000ff> <TR><TD><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="3" COLOR="#000000"><FONT SIZE=-1> <A NAME=POST2021>  By <B><!-Email-!><A HREF="javascript:alert('The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.')" onMouseOver="window.status = 'The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.'; return true"><!-/Email-!><!-Name-!>Solla ElfHunter<!-/Name-!></A></B> on Wednesday, April 24, 2002 - 04:46 pm:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><P> <!-Text-!> Solla lept to her feet, dropping her potatoe and her paring knife.  At last something she wouldn&#39;t be ashamed to be caught doing was mentioned. <BR> <BR>&#34;I&#39;ve never been very crafty, but I&#39;m more than willing to try to pound out some armor thin,&#34; she said, smiling happily at Emmrald.  She handed the frilly apron back to Emmrald with a horrified look on her face.  &#34;I&#39;m sure there&#39;s a smith&#39;s apron at the forge, if you can show me the way.&#34; <BR> <BR>Solla had never been very fond of food that didn&#39;t start it&#39;s life running, flying or fishing.  &#34;If it doesn&#39;t move, don&#39;t eat it!&#34; her ma had always said.  After peeling a dozen or so potatoes, she was certain they never moved.  If it doesn&#39;t move, throw it in the fire.  Solla liked that idea so much better.  If it has to be wrapped in armor, so be it. <BR> <BR>Solla headed out to the forge while Diamond scrounged around for old armor.  There wasn&#39;t any kindling by the forge, but there were some large logs.  She headed out into the woods to pick up some small twigs and branches.  Except that her armor, bow and spear were in Diamond&#39;s house, she would take off running and never been seen passing this way again.  Argh!  Cooking!  A fire and a stick, a fire and a stick!  That&#39;s the way to cook. <!-/Text-!> <P> 
