<!-Post: 2048-!><!-Time: 1020525042-!>
<TABLE BGCOLOR=#ccffff WIDTH=60% BORDER=0 BORDERCOLOR=#0000ff> <TR><TD><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial,Helvetica" SIZE="3" COLOR="#000000"><FONT SIZE=-1> <A NAME=POST2048>  By <B><!-Email-!><A HREF="javascript:alert('The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.')" onMouseOver="window.status = 'The e-mail address and profile information for the individual posting this message is not available.'; return true"><!-/Email-!><!-Name-!>Solla ElfHunter<!-/Name-!></A></B> on Saturday, May 4, 2002 - 11:10 am:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><P> <!-Text-!> Solla had rekindled the fires in the forge.  She put the heavy leather apron on and was arranging the tools she needed.  She dragged the slack bucket a little closer to the anvil. Everything was ready when Diamond arrived with the armor pieces and ale.  A quick swig of ale and Solla picked up the first broken piece with thongs.  Solla held the piece in the fire as she worked the bellows with her foot. <BR> <BR>As she and Diamond talked about the various irregularities of husbands, children, kin and clan, Solla turned the armor piece, withdrawing it from the fire occasionally, checking it&#39;s color.  When she got it to a nice cherry glow, she held it on the anvil, and with a hot set, she cut the armor piece in half.  She threw the half in her thongs into the slack bucket, and picked up the other half and reheated it in the furnace. <BR> <BR>&#34;What sort of half-witted dwarf keeps a wolverine for a guard dog?  They may be furry and fiesty, but they&#39;re just no fun,&#34; said Solla as she pulled the iron out of the flames to check the color.  Cherry red, perfect. <BR> <BR>Holding the iron on the anvil she started drawing out the armor with a hammer.  She and Diamond discussed what the ideal lad would be like, and lamented the fact that none existed as she continued to reheat and draw out the iron.  <BR> <BR>&#34;How thin does Emmrald want this to be?&#34; Solla asked Diamond as she cut the iron in half with the hot set and threw half into the slack bucket.  The iron sizzled as it hit the water, steam rising up from the water.  This was hot and humid work.  When the sizzling stopped, Diamond took the piece out with thongs and set it aside for later reworking. <BR> <BR>&#34;Tin &#39;nough ta wrap &#39;round de tatters,&#34; said Diamond.  Solla and Diamond stared at each other, then started laughing.  &#34;Better ta be &#39;ere hammerin iron den in dere touchin tatters.&#34;  Solla nodded agreement and continued drawing out the iron. <!-/Text-!> <P> 
